## Code-Aware Tokenization — The Secret Sauce

Plain text tokenization doesn't work on code:

```python
# Plain split:
"executeCode".split()  → ["executeCode"]  # one big token, useless

# Our tokenizer:
tokenize_code("executeCode")  → ["execute", "code"]  # now "execute code" matches!
```

### The Four Steps

```python
def tokenize_code(text):
    # Step 1: camelCase → separate words
    "executeCode"    → "execute Code"
    "DataProcessor"  → "Data Processor"
    
    # Step 2: ALLCAPS → separate
    "HTMLParser"     → "HTML Parser"
    
    # Step 3: Replace non-letters with spaces
    "validate_input" → "validate input"     # underscores
    "parser/code.py" → "parser code py"     # paths
    "a.b.c"          → "a b c"              # dots
    
    # Step 4: Lowercase + remove tiny tokens
    "Data Processor" → ["data", "processor"]
    "a b c"          → ["c"]                # "a" and "b" dropped (too short)
```

### Why This Matters

Without this tokenization:
- Searching "execute code" would NOT match `executeCode`
- Searching "data processor" would NOT match `DataProcessor`
- Searching "validate input" would NOT match `validate_input`

With it, all these queries work because both sides get the same tokens.

